  <p class="article-lede">Ghana's fintech sector scores 7.0 out of 10, with a STABLE_UP trend. That number conceals a bifurcation that matters more than the headline: consumer-facing fintech is crowded, low-moat, and increasingly fragile, while B2B infrastructure and diaspora remittance corridors remain genuinely underbuilt. The money is not where most founders are looking.</p>

  <p>The macro backdrop has improved significantly. The Bank of Ghana cut its policy rate by 150 basis points to 14% in March 2026 (by a 3-1-1 vote on the Monetary Policy Committee). Inflation sits at 3.3%, the lowest since August 1999. The 91-day Treasury bill rate has compressed to approximately 15%, delivering a real return of roughly 1.5%. GDP growth is running at 6.0%, and the cedi has stabilized at GHS 10.97 to the US dollar after a 29% appreciation over the prior 12 months.</p>

  <p>These numbers create a window for fintech. Lower lending rates mean cheaper capital for fintech operators. Better macro stability means fewer defaults on digital credit products. Diaspora remittances hit $7.8 billion in 2025 (Bank of Ghana), creating a transaction volume pool that dwarfs most domestic revenue opportunities.</p>

  <p>But the window is narrower than it appears. Regulation is tightening, the e-levy continues to distort digital payment behavior, and the best consumer niches are already occupied by well-funded incumbents. This analysis maps where value actually remains.</p>

