  <h2 id="watch-next">What to Watch Next</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>April/May CPI readings:</strong> If inflation stays below 5%, the macro tailwind continues and further BoG rate cuts are possible in H2 2026. If inflation exceeds 5% (plausible due to Hormuz fuel transmission), the rate-cutting cycle pauses and fintech lending economics tighten.</li>
    <li><strong>E-levy collection data:</strong> The Ghana Revenue Authority's quarterly collection figures reveal whether the e-levy is generating sufficient revenue to be maintained or whether political pressure for reduction is building. Low collections strengthen the case for reduction or elimination.</li>
    <li><strong>BoG licensing actions:</strong> Any new enforcement actions against unlicensed digital lenders signal tightening regulation. This benefits licensed operators but raises the barrier for new entrants.</li>
    <li><strong>Diaspora legislation cluster:</strong> The Diaspora Participation Bill (GANRAP passed in Cycle 040) and GIPC reform create potential regulatory tailwinds for diaspora-focused fintech products. Watch for implementation timelines; enacted legislation without implementation is common in Ghana.</li>
    <li><strong>LemFi, NALA, Pesa growth metrics:</strong> These corridor-focused players are the bellwethers for remittance fintech. If their Ghana volumes continue growing, the corridor opportunity is validated. If growth stalls, competition or regulatory friction may be binding.</li>
    <li><strong>GhIPSS transaction volumes:</strong> Quarterly GhIPSS data reveals whether digital payment adoption is growing despite the e-levy headwind. Stagnant or declining volumes would indicate that the e-levy distortion is worsening.</li>
  </ul>

